item.title: ‚ö†Ô∏è‚ÄºÔ∏è THIS WAS TOUGH ü•∫ | Ft Sunitha Krishnan | Telugu Podcast | Raw Talks With VK
item.description:
Sunitha Krishnan: a Padma Shri awardee, Indian social entrepreneur ; co-founder of Prajwala Foundation, one of world‚Äôs largest anti-trafficking shelters that rescues, rehabilitates and reintegrates victims into society.
She‚Äôs also an author ‚ÄúI Am What I Am": A Memoir You can find the book here ! - https://www.amazon.in/Am-What-Memoir-ebook/dp/B0D731BFKD
In this Telugu podcast episode, social activist Sunitha Krishnan shares the journey behind one of India‚Äôs most urgent yet least understood human rights challenges, preventing child sexual abuse, human trafficking, and cyber-enabled exploitation.
From her role in pushing for the National Cyber Crime Reporting Portal to exposing how child sexual abuse material (CSAM) circulates across social media, messaging platforms, and hidden digital networks, this conversation sheds light on what often remains unseen.
Sunitha Krishnan explains why the term is not ‚Äúchild pornography‚Äù but CSAM, how demand fuels trafficking, and how technology has quietly enabled exploitation through coded language, online marketplaces, and encrypted platforms. Drawing from real cases in India and abroad, she discusses the psychological impact on survivors, the toll on investigators, and the systems that allow abuse to continue when society looks away.
The episode also examines secondary victimisation, gaps in legal processes, victim-blaming narratives, and the urgent need for greater accountability from technology companies. She speaks about her work with Prajwala Foundation, the resilience of survivors, children born into red-light areas, and why rehabilitation, education, and dignity matter far more than sympathy.
From Supreme Court advocacy to survivor rehabilitation, and from hard questions around gender, demand, and responsibility to pathways for real reform, this is an intense, honest, and necessary conversation.
This episode is a powerful reminder of why child safety, women‚Äôs rights, cyber crime prevention, and social justice demand our attention. It will challenge how you think, without shouting, without simplifying, and without turning away.

In this video, I unbox the ECOVACS DEEBOT N20 Pro and share my first impressions + initial cleaning test: vacuum performance, vibrating mopping (OZMO Pro), mapping, app control, noise, and real-world usage on Indian floors (dust, hair, corners, carpets).
In this video, I compare Ecovacs Deebot N20 Pro vs Deebot N30 vs Deebot N30 Plus ‚Äî which one gives the best value for Indian homes (dust, hair, tiles, corners, carpets).
‚úÖ Key highlights (as per listed specs):‚Ä¢ 8000Pa suction power for deep cleaning ‚Ä¢ OZMO Pro vibrating mopping system (better than drag-only mops) ‚Ä¢ ZeroTangle / anti-hair tangle tech for pet/human hair ‚Ä¢ 5200mAh battery + claimed up to ~300 mins runtime / large home coverage üí∞ Current price reference (may change): around ‚Çπ28,999 on major platforms (India).
Unboxing Contents: The box includes the robot (white color), charging dock, side brush, anti-tangle main brush, washable mopping pads, a "dummy" tank (for vacuum-only mode), and a vibrating mopping module (OZMO Pro 2.0). Key Features & Upgrades (vs. Y1 Pro): * Suction Power: Upgraded to 8000 Pa (compared to lower suction on older models). * Runtime: Up to 300 minutes on a single charge. * Mopping: Features a vibrating mopping system (OZMO Pro 2.0) for better stain removal, unlike the static mop on the Y1 Pro. * Tangle-Free: Uses ZeroTangle‚Ñ¢ Technology (mentioned as "anti-tangle" in the video) with flat bristles and comb teeth to prevent hair buildup. Maintenance Tips (from Ecovacs Rep): * Dust Bin: 400ml capacity; the filter should be dry-cleaned (tapped or brushed), not washed with water. * Sensors: Clean the anti-drop and bumper sensors weekly with a dry cloth or earbud. * Tanks: Use the "dummy tank" when only vacuuming to maintain weight balance. Use the water tank only for mopping and fill with plain water (no chemical cleaners). * Brushes: The side and main brushes are detachable for easy cleaning of any trapped hair.

item.description:
Vishakha Sadhwani: I NEVER Thought This Would Happen To Me! | Vishakha Sadhwani
I was the quiet, underconfident middle child who never imagined she‚Äôd end up in big tech, let alone in a different country.
And if you saw where I am today, you might think I always had everything figured out. But the truth is‚Ä¶ my entire career started because of one unexpected moment.
I missed my DU application deadline. A form didn‚Äôt reach on time, and the path I had planned for years disappeared overnight.
What felt like a massive failure back then quietly pushed me toward engineering‚Ä¶ and then toward opportunities I never would‚Äôve considered if life had gone ‚Äúaccording to plan.‚Äù
By my third year, I realised I wanted more than the predictable path everyone around me was taking. So I prepared on my own, took my exams, and moved to the U.S. for my Master‚Äôs.
That one decision changed everything.
It led me to three job offers after graduation, to AWS, to Google New York, to global conferences, to recognition from major publications, to the EB1A visa, and eventually to NVIDIA in California. It also helped me build a community of thousands of people who support me every day.
And all of this came from a moment I once thought was the end of my plans.
Sometimes the door that closes‚Ä¶ is the one that makes space for something bigger.

item.title: Rating Top Programming Languages | Vishakha Sadhwani #shorts
item.description:
Vishakha Sadhwani: Rating Top Programming Languages
If you don‚Äôt want to get replaced by AI and want to stay relevant, you need to PRACTICE the right coding languages! In this short, I rate the top programming languages of 2025, and here‚Äôs why:
R (4/10) Great for research and stats, but very few companies outside academia actually need it.
C# (6/10) Perfect for Microsoft .NET and Unity game dev, but not very common in AI or open-source projects.
Java (7/10) Decades old and still powering banking systems and Android apps. Around 30% of developers still use it, which shows its reliability, even if it‚Äôs not the ‚Äúhot‚Äù choice anymore.
HTML/CSS (5.5/10) The basics of web development. Everyone learns them, but on their own, they won‚Äôt take you far without JavaScript.
Rust (6.5/10) Loved by developers for speed and safety. Even though it was voted the ‚Äúmost loved‚Äù language on Stack Overflow, jobs are still limited compared to Python or Java.
Go (7/10) The go-to for cloud and DevOps. Companies like Google and teams working on Kubernetes rely on it, though it‚Äôs not as universal as Python or JavaScript.
JavaScript (8/10) The universal language of the web. Nearly 2 out of 3 developers use it, and every company with a website depends on it. But it struggles with compute-heavy tasks compared to C++ or Python.
TypeScript (8.5/10) Brings scalability and safety to JavaScript projects. Companies love it for large applications, making it one of the fastest-growing skills in demand.
Python (9/10) From AI to data science to cloud, Python is everywhere. Beginner-friendly yet powerful, and one of the most in-demand languages with recruiters today. Share this with your friends and follow me for more!
Make sure to like, share, and subscribe so you don‚Äôt miss more content like this!

In this video, I've talked about the top 5 programming languages you must learn in 2026 for a strong and future-ready tech career. You'll learn why these programming languages matter, where they are used, and how they'll help you get high-paying tech jobs in 2026.

If you're a college student, a coding newbie, or a working professional planning a switch to software engineering, cloud, or DevOps, this video will guide you in the right direction. These languages are widely used in backend development, full-stack projects, and cloud computing.
Make sure to watch till the end and share it with someone who wants to learn programming or grow in tech.

item.title: Failing IAS To Cracking MAANG Companies - My Journey
item.description:
Vishakha Sadhwani: From Failed IAS Attempt to Google, AWS and NVIDIA | My Journey
I‚Äôd always been a studious kid. My dream was to become an IAS officer. So, after acing all my exams in 12th grade, I applied to Delhi University to get my bachelor‚Äôs with big hopes and a heart full of ambition. But life had something else in mind. My application form, which I‚Äôd sent by post, never arrived on time. Even though my marks were good enough to secure a seat, fate quietly rerouted my journey.
When the DU and IAS dream slipped away, my dad wanted me to pursue engineering. Honestly, I wasn‚Äôt excited about it, but I went ahead and got into one of the top universities in my home state of Chhattisgarh. And that‚Äôs where everything slowly began to change.
By the time I reached my third year, while most of my friends were preparing for CAT or GATE, I realized I wanted something different. I skipped campus placements, studied on my own, and took the GRE and TOEFL exams and to my surprise, scored well in both.
Soon after, I moved to the U.S. to pursue my Master‚Äôs in Computer Engineering at the University of Maryland, my biggest leap yet. And that decision changed everything.
‚Üí Graduated with three job offers ‚Üí Later, got into AWS and was even featured on their website ‚Üí Joined Google in New York ‚Üí Earned promotions, awards, and even fully sponsored holidays ‚Üí Featured on Google‚Äôs official Instagram and YouTube accounts ‚Üí Recognized by publications like Business Insider, Tech Times, Tech Bullion, and more ‚Üí Spoke at several international conferences ‚Üí Received the EB1 A ‚ÄúEinstein‚Äù Visa ‚Üí Joined NVIDIA in 2025 as a Senior Solutions Architect and moved to California ‚Üí Built a thriving community of over 100K on LinkedIn and 15K on Instagram
Looking back, I realize that life always knows where to take you, even when things don‚Äôt go as planned. That one missed form led me on a journey I never imagined, and today, both I and my family couldn‚Äôt be happier seeing how far things have come.
